      "ocr_text": "Any line breaks or other changes must be accurately captured and recreated with the original text in the image.\nThe growth of Communist movements in regions along the Silk Road has been significant. The Kuwaiti nationalists, for example, have been pressing the Kuwaiti family, which has a long history of resistance, to return to the old order. The British military presence has also contributed to the situation. The British government has also been accused of using its military presence to suppress the local population's demand for more autonomy.\nRelations between the Kuwaiti Government and the British have been tense at times. The British military adviser has been accused of being too pro-American and too willing to use force. The British military has also been accused of using its presence in the Kuwaiti region to suppress local aspirations for self-determination.\nThe Kuwaiti authorities have cracked down hard on anti-Qasim activism by pro-UAR Kuwaiti nationalists, and otherwise striven to avoid antagonizing Iraq. The main impetus to the current anti-Qasim sentiment in the Kuwaiti region is the public attack on the Kuwaiti regime at a nationalist rally on 1 February honoring formation of the UAR. If the Kuwaiti regime's repression is not followed by a meaningful attempt to liberalize the apparatus of government, however, the hitherto moderate nationalist opposition may be driven to advocate more uncompromising resistance. The ruler of Kuwaiti has balanced his action by informing the Egyptian-dominated Arab League of readiness to contribute $14,000,000 to the Arab Economic Organization.\nWhile the pro-UAR nationalists have been temporarily",
